(43, 6, 17, 43, 2, 12, 12, 'Capernaum', 'Journey to Capernaum', 'Both passages emphasize the journey to Capernaum, highlighting its significance in Jesus'' ministry. The mention of Capernaum in both contexts connects the events surrounding Jesus and his disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 17, 43, 4, 46, 46, 'Capernaum', 'Journey to Capernaum', 'Both passages emphasize Capernaum as a significant location. In John 6:17, the disciples are traveling toward Capernaum, while in John 4:46, Jesus is noted to have returned to Cana, where a nobleman''s son is sick in Capernaum.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 18, 19, 107, 25, 25, 'the sea arose by reason of a great wind', 'Connection of Storm Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the power of the wind and its ability to raise the sea. John 6:18 describes a stormy sea due to a great wind, while Psalms 107:25 speaks of God commanding the stormy wind that lifts waves.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 18, 19, 135, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Wind and Sea', 'Both passages emphasize the role of wind in natural phenomena. John 6:18 describes a sea affected by a great wind, while Psalms 135:7 speaks of God bringing forth wind from his treasuries, suggesting divine control over nature.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 18, 40, 14, 24, 24, 'the sea arose by reason of a great wind that blew', 'Connection of Storm Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the tumultuous nature of the sea due to strong winds. The ''great wind'' in John 6:18 parallels the ''contrary'' wind in Matthew 14:24, highlighting the challenges faced by the disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 41, 6, 47, 49, 'walking on the sea', 'Connection of Jesus Walking on Water', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus walking on the sea during a time of distress for the disciples. They highlight the fear experienced by the disciples upon seeing him, indicating a shared experience of confusion and fear in the presence of the miraculous.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 40, 14, 25, 26, 'walking on the sea', 'Jesus Walking on Water', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus walking on the sea, which causes fear among the disciples. The shared theme of fear in response to seeing Jesus highlights the miraculous nature of the event.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 18, 9, 8, 8, NULL, 'Divine Authority Over Nature', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over the sea. Both passages emphasize the act of ''treading upon the waves of the sea,'' showcasing God''s power and Jesus'' divine nature.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 19, 93, 4, 4, NULL, 'Divine Power Over Water', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power over the sea. In John 6:19, Jesus walks on the sea, demonstrating His authority, while Psalms 93:4 emphasizes that the Lord is mightier than the waves of the sea.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 43, 14, 18, 18, NULL, 'Presence and Comfort in Fear', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' presence during times of fear. In John 6:19, the disciples are afraid when they see Jesus walking on the sea, while in John 14:18, Jesus assures them of His comforting presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 32, 1, 13, 13, NULL, 'Fear in the Midst of Storms', 'Both passages emphasize the struggle against a tempestuous sea. In John, the disciples are afraid as they see Jesus walking on the water, while in Jonah, the men row hard against a violent storm. This connection highlights the theme of fear and divine intervention in perilous situations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 19, 19, 29, 10, 10, NULL, 'Divine Sovereignty Over Water', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s authority over chaotic waters. In John 6:19, Jesus walks on the sea, demonstrating His power, while Psalms 29:10 affirms the Lord''s kingship over the flood.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 40, 14, 27, 31, 'It is I; be not afraid', 'Connection of Jesus'' Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' comforting words, ''It is I; be not afraid.'' This connection highlights the theme of reassurance in moments of fear.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 23, 43, 1, 2, 'be not afraid', 'Fear Not and Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the reassurance to not fear in the presence of God. John 6:20''s ''It is I; be not afraid'' echoes Isaiah 43:1-2''s ''Fear not'' and highlights God''s promise to be with His people through trials.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 23, 44, 8, 8, 'be not afraid', 'Fear Not Theme Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the reassurance against fear. In John 6:20, Jesus tells his disciples, ''be not afraid,'' while Isaiah 44:8 encourages not to fear, asserting God''s uniqueness and presence.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 66, 1, 17, 18, 'be not afraid', 'Fear Not Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Fear not,'' indicating a reassurance from Jesus. This connection highlights the continuity of Christ''s presence and comfort in both the Gospels and Revelation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 41, 6, 50, 50, 'it is I; be not afraid', 'Connection of Comforting Words', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''it is I; be not afraid,'' which serves as a comforting reassurance to the disciples in moments of fear. This connection highlights the consistent message of Jesus providing peace in times of distress.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 19, 35, 3, 3, 'be not afraid', 'Fear and Divine Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of reassurance in times of fear. In John 6:20, the phrase ''be not afraid'' directly addresses fear, while Psalms 35:3 conveys a plea for divine salvation amidst persecution, suggesting a need for comfort and strength.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 20, 41, 16, 6, 6, 'be not afraid', 'Fear and Assurance in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''be not afraid,'' providing reassurance in moments of fear. In John, Jesus calms his disciples, while in Mark, the angel reassures the women at the tomb.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 21, 41, 6, 51, 51, 'received him into the ship', 'Connection of Jesus and the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' presence in the ship and the immediate calming of the situation. In John, the ship reaches its destination after receiving Jesus, while in Mark, the wind ceases when He enters the ship.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 21, 40, 14, 32, 33, 'immediately the ship was at the land', 'Worship and Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of recognition of Jesus'' divine nature by the disciples after he calms the storm. In John, the immediate arrival at land signifies his authority, while in Matthew, the disciples worship him, acknowledging him as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 21, 19, 24, 7, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Glory and Arrival', 'This connection highlights the theme of welcoming the divine presence. In both passages, there is an emphasis on receiving and recognizing the King of glory, suggesting a parallel in the acknowledgment of Jesus'' authority and divinity as he arrives.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 21, 66, 3, 20, 20, 'willingly received him into the ship', 'Invitation and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of welcoming Jesus. In both passages, there is an emphasis on receiving Him, whether into a ship or into one''s life.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 21, 22, 3, 4, 4, 'received him into the ship', 'Connection of Seeking and Receiving', 'Both passages emphasize the act of finding and receiving a beloved figure. In John 6:21, the disciples willingly receive Jesus into the ship, while in Song of Solomon 3:4, the speaker finds and holds onto their beloved.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 22, 41, 6, 45, 45, 'his disciples were gone away alone', 'Disciples'' Journey Across the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize the movement of the disciples across the sea. In John, the disciples are noted to have gone away alone, while in Mark, Jesus constrained them to get into the ship and go to the other side.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 22, 40, 14, 22, 22, 'his disciples were gone away alone', 'Disciples'' Departure in Boats', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples getting into a ship to cross to the other side. This connection highlights the action of the disciples leaving without Jesus, which is central to both narratives.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 22, 43, 6, 2, 2, NULL, 'Following Jesus and His Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the multitude that followed Jesus due to his miracles. The crowd''s pursuit in John 6:2 sets the stage for the events described in John 6:22, where the disciples leave without Jesus, indicating the ongoing interest in his actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 22, 43, 6, 15, 21, 'his disciples were gone away alone', 'Disciples'' Journey and Jesus'' Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' journey across the sea and their experience of Jesus'' miraculous presence. In John 6:15-21, the disciples are in a boat without Jesus, while John 6:22 highlights that the people noticed Jesus did not accompany them. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' separation and subsequent appearance to his disciples.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 23, 43, 6, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Location and Context', 'Both passages emphasize the geographical setting of the Sea of Tiberias, linking the events surrounding Jesus'' actions. The mention of Tiberias in both verses establishes a continuity in the narrative about Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
